          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "I'll calculate the present value and payment details for a 30-year loan of $500,000 at 10% annual interest.\n\n## Monthly Payment Formula\n\nFor a loan, the monthly payment is calculated using:\n\n**PMT = P × [r(1 + r)^n] / [(1 + r)^n - 1]**\n\nWhere:\n- P = Principal ($500,000)\n- r = Monthly interest rate (10% / 12 = 0.008333)\n- n = Number of payments (30 years × 12 = 360 months)\n\n## Calculation\n\n```\nr = 0.10 / 12 = 0.008333\nn = 30 × 12 = 360\n\nPMT = 500,000 × [0.008333(1.008333)^360] / [(1.008333)^360 - 1]\n    = 500,000 × [0.008333 × 19.8374] / [19.8374 - 1]\n    = 500,000 × [0.1653] / [18.8374]\n    = 500,000 × 0.008776\n    = $4,387.86\n```\n\n## Results\n\n- **Monthly Payment**: $4,387.86\n- **Total Paid**: $4,387.86 × 360 = $1,579,629.60\n- **Total Interest**: $1,579,629.60 - $500,000 = $1,079,629.60\n\n## Net Present Value (NPV)\n\nIf we discount those monthly payments back at the same 10% rate:\n\n**NPV = Σ [PMT / (1 + r)^t] for t = 1 to 360**\n\nThis simplifies to the present value of an annuity formula, which equals:\n\n**NPV = $500,000** (the original loan amount)\n\nThis makes sense: when you discount future payments at the same rate as the loan's interest rate, the present value equals the principal borrowed."
          }
        ],
